Cedric,

I think there&#39;s a lot of room for different ways of organizing tests. 
For me, it&#39;s good for JUnit 4 to keep the one-class-instance-per-test 
philosophy of JUnits 1 through 3. I find that if my code depends on too 
much global state, or too many collaborators, I begin to feel it, 
because it gets harder to test in JUnit. I find that if I ignore this 
pain in the tests, eventually it becomes a pain in the code, so I like 
JUnit&#39;s early warning.

With that in mind, I find that having the parameters on the constructor 
reminds me of what&#39;s really going on.

David Saff

Cédric Beust ♔ wrote:

&gt; Hi Kent,
&gt;
&gt; On 10/4/05, Kent Beck &lt;kentb@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Cedric,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; If I need different sets of parameters for different tests, I put the
&gt; &gt; tests
&gt; &gt; in different classes. This way, tests don&#39;t see parameters they don&#39;t
&gt; &gt; need.
&gt; &gt; The same goes for fields set in a set-up method. Only tests that need
&gt; &gt; exactly the same setup go in the same class.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Well, that&#39;s certainly the way it works in JUnit3, but I thought the whole
&gt; point behind the parameterized proposal was to allow tests to receive
&gt; parameters?
&gt;
&gt; A lot of TestNG users like this feature, so that instead of passing, say,
&gt; the path of an XML file in the constructor and then referencing it in your
&gt; test method:
&gt;
&gt; public VerifyXmlTest(String xmlPath) {
&gt; this.xmlPath = xmlPath;
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; public void testXml() {
&gt; // use this.xmlPath
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; You pass it directly to the test method:
&gt;
&gt; public void testXml(String xmlPath) {
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; Cleaner, and it also features better isolation since you are not exposing
&gt; this parameter to test methods that don&#39;t need it.
&gt;
&gt; --
&gt; Cédric
